Yes, we should decide what the presets point to and why. I don't even remember
what I said about the presets already and I can't find it in the transcripts.
Destinations I think the Netheress are likelty to have found and bookmarked,
besides the nine hells, are the Feywild, Shadowfell and The Seven Heavens. My
thinking is that The Feywild and Shadowfell are canonically "parallel" to the
prime material, and the hells and heavens are the extremes of "good" and "bad"
and therefore easier to find. I'm open to suggestions though.


It's up to the kids to decide what to do about the portal, but I'm pretty sure
they want to keep it secret both for their sake and for everyone else's. I
think they also want to keep it pointed to as safe of a destination as
possible, which might just be the outskirts of the hells, and maybe that's
_why_ it was pointed there.


Inn decisions can wait. As far as the kids are concerned, Lord Neverember is
on top of that. He'll assign a lacky to do the actual organization and there
won't be any evidence of the new business in town for at least a couple of
days. They will likely re-purpose whatever building is across from the
existing inn so customers can see both choices at the same time, and that
means they'll have to pay whoever's there now to move and they will either
take the existing building down because it wasn't built to last or retrofit
it. All that's going to take a while to orchestrate. Unless the kids do an
exploration montage in the Netherese base, they'll be back in town the same
day they left.

I expect the kids would love to be involved in the inn development. Whoever
Neverember puts in charge will have final say but they'l be happy to get input
from Smol and Sonbgird.


I envision Neverember's team as four regular adventurers and two planar
specialists/scholars. (This would make a good seed for a game of its own!) I
figure it's the standard Tank, DPS, Controller, Healer template plus the
specialists. At least one of the first four should have some extra-planar
experience, just so they know what to expect from planar travel.

I'd like a rich mix of species, classes, alignments and such. I think I might
have the kids make some of the decisions for these NPCs so that I don't
outnumber the two players at the table so much, but I want the NPC's character
sheets fully filled out and I'll want to sketch backstories for them. We'll
about that in a bit.

Regarding arrival time: they're coming from Waterdeep and Neverwinter, so
travel time from those places plus one day to actually recruit them.

The specialists are going to be experts in their field who work at whatever
the biggest research institutions on The Sword Coast are. The other four will
be seasoned adventurers who have been adventuring together for a while and
just wrapped up another big job in one of the two big cities. They're
loyalties lie with themselves, then each other, then money, then the client.
Neverember knows them because he hired them for their most recent job. He's
always paying adventurers to handle things he can't do officially. This is one
of the few groups he works with who know they've been working for him. Usually
he uses an intermediary to protect his reputation. The adventurers have no
hidden agenda. They're in it for glory and gold. The scholars... maybe? I need
to think about that.


Doom clocks:

I'm glad you reminded me about Elder Thuul. I think she's super smart, by any
standards, goblin or otherwise, and decides to send a squad to the mountain to
keep an eye on it. The goblin squad are smart enough not to tangle with the
facility defenses, but they'll know the bulettes have been driven from the
mountain because the ones that ran away will have been seen fighting with the
local wildlife. I suppose they'll also see the owlbears pursuing the bulettes
since that's their original food source on the mountain. But the kids won't
know any of this. I'm just mentioning it to keep track of in the notes.

The situation with the Redbrands is interesting. I think they must know the
kids left town because the town would have talked about it. They kids are
celebrities in Phandalin now. Hm. I bet the mayor is hoping to use the
Redbrands as a potential backup plan for taking control of the facility
because he doesn't know that the kids have hero's advantage. Anyway, I think
the Redbrands guessed the kids triggered the light show, so they're preparing
to try to steal the facility form them when they come back. But they don't
have the resources to track the kids remotely with scrying and such, so
they're just going to wait in Phandalin, do minor crimes to sustain themselves
and hope to catch the kids off guard whenever they come back.

With the Owlbears, I think the one they interacted with in session 2 has been
awakened and wants to reconnect with them, so if they don't show up in the
next week she'll go looking for them. Can they fly? Or are they more bear than
owl? https://www.dndbeyond.com/monsters/5195152-owlbear only lists speed and
climb speed, no fly speed, so I'm guessing no. Their move speed is 40 which
comes to about 4.5 mph if they never stop. I guess she won't go looking for
them. If they come back within a week, the whole owlbear family will still be
on the mountain, otherwise it will just be the mama bear who is waiting for
them to come back. If they do take more than a week (four days left) to return
to the facility, I will have Carl relay a message from the facility that a
single owlbear stayed behind after the rest left. That is sure to tug at their
heart strings and bring them back. :)

And that will be an opportunity for the Redbrands to jump them. Which means
the Redbrands need to be ready in five days at most. I think they might not be
ready, especially if the party brings their Neverember-assigned escort with
them. Which they might not. Who knows!


The status of the facility

- They already received an update about the bulettes being gone. That means
  the facility's resources can be fully devoted to repairs, hardening defenses
  and building the lower levels that Ray defined before he died.
- Primus-3R is fully repaired and getting crystal production back online.
- In five more days defenses will be fully hardened, meaning the mountain will
  be bristling with defensive equipment disguised as folliage and rocks, and
  there will be a lot more robots available to patrol the internal perimiters.
- I just realized the facility doesn't know its new adminstrators like the
  owlbears. That changes things. Mama owlbear is going to have to leave the
  mountain's defensive perimiter. I guess she'll be in the foothills living
  off of wolves, boars, deer, etc.
- So, as of start of session 8, the owlbears are traveling down the mountain
  as the facility restores its defenses, and in four more in-game days that
  will be done, they'll get a message about it and the facility will resume
  its default programming to work on the lower levels. That work has months to
  go. The area is still getting hollowed out, then it needs to be wired and
  plummed, then it needs to have the new, larger anvil built. I'm imagining it
  being a mechanism the size of a BelAZ 75710: 30' tall, 35' wide, 70' long.
  Ray had big ideas. It will also take months to expand the energy capture
  system sufficiently to run the thing.


